==Chinese==

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}
{{liushu|p}}: multiple neatly arranged fruits or thorns. The oracle bone script of {{zh-l|櫅}} depicts these growing on a tree.

Possibly related to {{zh-l|薺}} ({{zh-l|蒺藜}}, a plant with thorny fruits) and {{zh-l|櫅}} (white jujube).

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|s=齐|alt=斉,斊,立,亝,𠫼,𠄷}}
Either related to {{cog|lus|čelʔᴸ||equal, to endure}} or, more phonologically likely, {{cog|bo|ཚིར||queue, order, succession}} as Tibetan {{IPAfont|/tsʰir/}}'s final {{IPAfont|/-r/}} can explain the Middle Chinese retroflex initial of {{och-l|儕}}, which is derived from {{och-l|齊|id=1}}. Note also similarities to {{cog|my|စီ|t=to line up}},<ref>{{R:sit:Luce 1981|page=11|head=-I and -E Finals (28. to Set in order, Arrange)}}</ref> {{m|my|စေ့|t=to keep things close together}}.<ref>{{R:sit:Luce 1981|page=11|head=-I and -E Finals (27. Complete; Uniform)}}</ref>

